03871nam a22005055i 9780773565487DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19951995xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735654877 a10.1515/97807735654872doi  a(DE-B1597)656148  a(OCoLC)732600760  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aNC1446bM673 1995eb 7aSOC0080002bisacsh04a971.4/041 aMorris, Raymond N., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCarnivalization of Politics :bQuebec Cartoons on Relations with Canada, England, and France, 1960-1979 /cRaymond N. Morris. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1995] 4cÂ©1995  a1 online resource (160 p.) :b21 b&w diagrams and cartoons  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tAcknowledgments -- tEditorial Cartoons as Social Documents -- tRelations with In-Laws: Berthio Greets the Queen -- tRelations with Parents: Dupras Welcomes President de Gaulle -- tQuebec and Ottawa as Spouses: Can They Live Together? -- tThe Fragmentation of Evangelicalism and the Transformation of TraditionOttawa and Quebec: Can They Live Apart? -- tBetween Parent and Child: Quebec and its Language Minority -- tConclusions -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExamining cartoons published between 1960 and 1979, Morris shows how the artists dealt with particular aspects of Quebec's political experience. He looks at Berthio's drawings on Queen Elizabeth's visit and Dupras's on President de Gaulle's; Girerd's and Berthio's on Quebec-Ottawa relations; Girerd's on the referendum campaign; and Girerd's and Aislin's on the English minority in Quebec. He points out recurring tensions, oppositions, and associations and analyses them from a sociological perspective. One of Morris's major objectives is to better understand the framework through which ideas presented in cartoons are filtered to their audience, focusing on the metaphors that underlie the frame, message, content, and form of the cartoons. Morris argues that the carnivalization of political figures and events, whereby the social structure is mockingly inverted and society's values and taboos are exaggerated until they become ridiculous, is a central metaphor governing Quebec cartoons of this period. He also explores the metaphor of the family, with England and France as grandparents, Canada and Quebec as parents, and the official-language minorities as children.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356548740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773565487423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773565487/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles